On Monday 04 December 2000 21:33, Thomas Wenzel wrote:

> Thomas or Hans-J=F6rg, can you tell me more please?
>
>  - Is the bus really only as slow as on the BlizzPPC / CVPPC?

The CVPPC does around 18-19 megs, the BVPPC AFAIK around 13. I don't thin=
k=20
that anything on the CPU bus can go that far. From what I heard the Media=
tor=20
should get around 7-8 MB/s

>  - If yes, is it fast enough to handle the high triangle coordinate
>    throughput required by modern games?

It depends on how triangle data is transmitted. The Voodoo has an=20
incremential setup stage (similar to the Permedia2) where you can output=20
triangle fans or strips in the natural way - by simply transfering the=20
vertices one by one.=20

Vertex data on the Voodoo is four longs for coordinates (x,y,z,w), one lo=
ng=20
for ARGB, two longs for s/t, making 7 long words per vertex, plus an=20
additional overhead of I think 12 longwords for the "usual" register stuf=
f=20
(that is color select, Z Buffer format/function etc). 5000 Triangles with=
 a=20
medium strip length of approx. 5 triangles (a rather optimistic assumptio=
n=20
:-) make approx. 1000 strips (with setup data) of 7 vertices each, that i=
s=20
196+48=3D244 bytes per triangle strip, or 244000 bytes per frame.

Assuming a bandwidth of 8 megs/s, this makes 34 frames per second with 50=
00=20
triangles each.

For a bandwidth of 18 megs/s, this yields 77 frames per second.

This is pure setup data. It does not take into account that some register=
=20
accesses on the voodoo actually cause a sync and thus finishes the curren=
t=20
drawing operation, and it does not consider the fill rate of the chip.

Also keep in mind that=20

a) this is pure number crunching and usually has nothing in common with=20
reality :-)

b) No texture uploads have been considered

c) in reality, the frame rates will be lower than this due to CPU power.

d) Engines like the Quake2 engine do multitexturing which is not (yet) pa=
rt=20
of Warp3D and hence require two triangles per visible triangle.

This only shows that in theory even 8 megs a second are enough to setup 5=
000=20
triangles per frame at 34 FPS. The 5000 figure is relatively realistic fo=
r=20
mid-range games, of course Quake 3 has a lot more of them :-)

